'''Mama Qucha''', also '''Mama Cocha''' ([[Quechuan languages|que.]] ''Sea Mother'') is the ancient [[Inca mythology|Incan]] goddess of sea and fishes, guardian of sailors and fishermen,{{r|Issitt}} wife of [[Viracocha]], mother of [[Inti]] and [[Mama Killa]].{{r|Roza}} In some regions of [[Inca Empire|empire]] people believed she was the goddess of all [[Body of water|bodies of water]], including lakes, rivers, and even human-made watercourses.{{r|Roza}} Mama Cocha was more important to people living beside the coastal regions due to nearness and dependence upon the sea.{{r|Roza}} Inca beliefs in Mama Cocha and other water deities indicate that the people back then understood the basics of the [[water cycle|hydrological cycle]]. They knew the [[seawater]] was replenishing the rain, which then fell over the ground.{{r|Issitt}}

