{{neutrality|date=September 2017}}
The '''Scientific study of religion''' represents the systematic effort by scholars and researchers to investigate religious phenomena, as well as the sociology of church participation.
The [[Society for the Scientific Study of Religion]] was founded in 1949 by scholars in religion and social science, and it publishes the ''[[Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion]]'', a quarterly which "offers perspectives on national and international issues such as brainwashing and cults, religious persecution, and [[right wing authoritarianism]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/journal.asp?ref=0021-8294&site=1 |title=Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion - Wiley Online Library |publisher=Blackwellpublishing.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-10}}</ref>
The Center for the Scientific Study of Religion (CSSR) at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] is a leading center for the sociology of religion, and particularly for the study of religious influences on human behavior and population outcomes. The CSSR went offline in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prc.utexas.edu/cssr/about_the_center/about_the_center.htm | publisher=University of Texas at Austin | work=Center for the Scientific Study of Religion (CSSR) | title=About the Center | accessdate=September 7, 2015 | author=Roemer, Michael K.| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609010657/http://www.prc.utexas.edu/cssr/about_the_center/about_the_center.htm | archivedate=June 9, 2007 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> <!-- Does the CSSR still exist? The only current ref I found was from 2003 --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.utexas.edu/features/archive/2003/religion.html | title=UT Feature Story --The Science of Religion: Researchers study how religious beliefs influence people's lives | publisher=University of Texas at Austin | work=Office of Public Affairs | date=2003 | accessdate=September 7, 2015 | author=Gerrow, Robin}}</ref>
